\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 AnythingLLM \'97 the best practical answer
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 AnythingLLM connects directly to your Google Drive and integrates with Ollama as the local LLM backend. You select the folders you want your LLM to "learn" from, it embeds the documents locally, and you can then query your entire Drive knowledge base through a chat interface \'97 all private.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://blog.neilhighley.com/2025/12/connect-ollama-to-your-google-drive-via-anythingllm/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 Neilhighley\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The setup flow is: install AnythingLLM 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  point it at your local Ollama 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  authenticate with Google Drive 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  select folders 
\f4 \uc0\u8594 
\f1  start asking questions. People describe it as the closest thing to a polished experience for this exact use case.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 What it can do with your Drive
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Once connected, you'd be able to ask things like:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls2\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "Summarize the key points from my woodworking project notes"\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "What did I write about my van camping trip to Oregon last summer?"\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "Find all documents related to my meal planning and give me a summary"\cb1 \
\ls2\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 "What CNC settings have I documented for hardwoods?"\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 It builds a local vector index of your documents so retrieval is fast and the LLM only sees the relevant chunks, not your entire Drive at once.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 The privacy nuance worth understanding
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This is where it gets slightly complicated. AnythingLLM pulls documents from Google Drive down to your Mac mini and indexes them locally \'97 so the\'a0
\f5\i analysis
\f1\i0 \'a0is fully private. But your documents still live in Google's cloud. That's an acceptable tradeoff for most people \'97 you're protecting the AI analysis of your data, not the storage of it. If you wanted truly air-gapped privacy, you'd sync Drive to local storage first and point AnythingLLM at the local folder instead.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 n8n as an alternative approach
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 If you want more control and automation, n8n has a native Ollama node and can trigger workflows from schedules or webhooks\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://dev.to/paarthurnax_3f967358857ce/how-to-run-ollama-on-mac-mini-a-complete-local-ai-setup-guide-4g5i"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 DEV Community\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 , so you could build a pipeline that periodically pulls new Drive documents, processes them through Ollama, and stores results locally. More setup work, but more flexible \'97 closer to the Python scripting approach you're already comfortable with.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Bottom line:
\f1\b0 \'a0AnythingLLM is the right starting point. It's the most mature, least-code-required path to querying your Google Drive content through a local model. Worth installing on the Mac mini before you write a single line of Python.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

