\cf2 \'a0There is no official API for personal shoppers to pull their own order history programmatically.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 The workarounds people actually use
\f1\b0 \cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Option 1 \'97 CSV export (manual but reliable)
\f1\b0 \'a0Amazon lets you download your order history as a CSV file directly from your account. It includes order date, order ID, items, quantities, and prices. You'd download it periodically and have your Mac mini process it through Ollama for categorization and YNAB posting. Not automated, but completely stable.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Option 2 \'97 Unofficial Python scraper
\f1\b0 \'a0The\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf12 \cb13 \strokec12 amazon-orders
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0library on PyPI provides an unofficial Python API that works by parsing data from Amazon's consumer-facing website. A periodic build validates its stability, but since Amazon provides no official API, this package may break at any time.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://github.com/alexdlaird/amazon-orders"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 GitHub\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \'a0Basic usage is straightforward:\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f0\fs18 \cf5 \cb14 \strokec5 python\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs21 \cf15 \cb14 \strokec15 from\cf16 \strokec16  amazonorders\cf17 \strokec17 .\cf16 \strokec16 session \cf15 \strokec15 import\cf16 \strokec16  AmazonSession\
\cf15 \strokec15 from\cf16 \strokec16  amazonorders\cf17 \strokec17 .\cf16 \strokec16 orders \cf15 \strokec15 import\cf16 \strokec16  AmazonOrders\
\
amazon_session = AmazonSession\cf17 \strokec17 (\cf18 \strokec18 "your@email.com"\cf17 \strokec17 ,\cf16 \strokec16  \cf18 \strokec18 "password"\cf17 \strokec17 )\cf16 \strokec16 \
amazon_session\cf17 \strokec17 .\cf16 \strokec16 login\cf17 \strokec17 ()\cf16 \strokec16 \
orders = AmazonOrders\cf17 \strokec17 (\cf16 \strokec16 amazon_session\cf17 \strokec17 ).\cf16 \strokec16 get_order_history\cf17 \strokec17 (\cf16 \strokec16 year=\cf19 \strokec19 2026\cf17 \strokec17 )\cf16 \cb1 \strokec16 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 The "may break at any time" caveat is real \'97 Amazon periodically changes their website structure and the library needs updates.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Option 3 \'97 Email parsing
\f1\b0 \'a0Amazon sends order confirmation and shipping emails. Your Mac mini could parse those via your local email, extract order details, and POST to YNAB. More reliable than scraping since email formats change less frequently.\cb1 \
\

\f2\b \cb3 Practical recommendation for your setup
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 For Amazon specifically, the CSV export + periodic processing is honestly the most reliable path. Download monthly, drop the file in a watched folder, let your Mac mini process it through Ollama for categorization, and POST the transactions to YNAB. Less elegant than a live API but immune to breaking changes. Combined with YNAB's bank connections catching your credit card charges, Amazon purchases showing up as a single charge from your card would already be in YNAB \'97 the CSV just adds the item-level detail if you want it.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

