\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 xCloud\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The retirement monitor you're envisioning sits perfectly in this paradigm. The system operates on a schedule, identifies what needs attention, and surfaces it \'97 without you having to remember to check anything. That's the core retirement-specific value: you stop\'a0
\f5\i worrying
\f1\i0 \'a0about whether you're paying attention to finances, because something is, and it'll tell you when you need to act.\cb1 \
\cb3 The total setup that emerges from combining all of this: you wake up, see a brief iMessage on your phone summarizing yesterday's finances and flagging anything unusual. You glance at it over coffee. You don't have to open YNAB unless something requires action. Weekly and monthly, slightly deeper reports arrive. Annually, the agent helps you do your tax prep and insurance shopping. All of it private, all of it on your hardware, all of it tuned to you and Anny specifically over time.\cb1 \
\cb3 That's a meaningful quality-of-life improvement for retirement \'97 not because budget tracking is hard, but because the\'a0
\f5\i decision to look
\f1\i0 \'a0at finances is what creates anxiety. Offloading that decision to a gentle automated system that only interrupts when warranted is the real value.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

