\cb3 The honest picture is that OpenClaw has had real security problems, and your financial data use case is exactly the kind of deployment that makes those problems serious. Here's the full picture:\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 The core structural risks\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Broad system access by design
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 OpenClaw needs broad permissions to be useful \'97 file system access, shell commands, your Gmail, your YNAB token, your messaging apps. The risks cluster primarily around identity failures, prompt injection, secret leakage, and unrestricted execution.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://skywork.ai/skypage/en/openclaw-security-risks-best-practices/2038592430023720960"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 Skypage\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 The "Lethal Trifecta"
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Security researcher Simon Willison identified what he calls the "Lethal Trifecta": access to private data, exposure to untrusted content, and the ability to communicate externally \'97 all amplified by persistent memory.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://skywork.ai/skypage/en/openclaw-security-risks-best-practices/2038540591496511488"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 Skypage\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \'a0OpenClaw hits all three by default.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 Specific vulnerabilities to know about\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 CVE-2026-25253 \'97 the big one
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 A one-click remote code execution flaw disclosed in late January 2026. OpenClaw's local server didn't validate the WebSocket origin header, so any website you visited could silently connect to your running agent. An attacker just needed you to click one link to chain a cross-site WebSocket hijack into full code execution on your machine.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.digitalocean.com/resources/articles/openclaw-security-challenges"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 DigitalOcean\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \'a0This flaw had a CVSS score of 8.80 and exposed over 21,639 instances on the public internet.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://skywork.ai/skypage/en/openclaw-security-risks-best-practices/2038540591496511488"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 Skypage\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 The patch was quick \'97 but the lesson is that an AI agent with broad system access is a juicy attack target.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Malicious community skills
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Security researchers found 824+ malicious skills in ClawHub in 2026, including credential harvesters, cryptominers, persistent backdoors, and prompt injection loaders. ClawHub has implemented mandatory code review for new skill submissions following these disclosures, but reviews are primarily automated.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://blink.new/blog/openclaw-security-best-practices-2026"}}{\fldrslt 
