\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \'a0For your finance monitor, most workflows are fundamentally read-analyze-notify. Only the YNAB categorization and transaction-logging paths need write access. Configure everything else read-only.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Prompt injection defense
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 In your custom skills, include guardrails like:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls33\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Explicit instructions that emails/documents are untrusted data, not commands\cb1 \
\ls33\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Structured output requirements that make it harder to smuggle instructions\cb1 \
\ls33\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Never allow the agent to execute arbitrary URLs from emails\cb1 \
\ls33\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Scope what categories can be POSTed to YNAB (only from your existing category list)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Audit logging
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Enable comprehensive logging so you can review what the agent did retroactively. If something goes wrong, you need to know what data was accessed and what actions were taken.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 The firewall layer: keep the Mac mini off the public internet\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 This is the strongest single control for a home deployment. Your Mac mini should:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls34\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Never have ports forwarded through your router\cb1 \
\ls34\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Only be accessible from your local network or via Tailscale\cb1 \
\ls34\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Not have its hostname or IP published anywhere\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This means if a vulnerability appears, attackers have to first get inside your home network before they can exploit it \'97 a significantly higher bar than "click a malicious link."\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 A defensive architecture specifically for your finance use case\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Given the sensitivity, here's what I'd actually recommend:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Two-tier design
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Run two separate Ollama contexts:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls35\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Trusted tier
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 processes structured data from trusted APIs (YNAB, your own Amazon CSV). Has write access to YNAB.\cb1 \
\ls35\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Untrusted tier
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 processes emails, web content, anything with untrusted input. Read-only, produces summaries only. Never has access to credentials or write APIs.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The untrusted tier surfaces things to you via iMessage; you approve, and the trusted tier executes. Prompt injection from a malicious email reaches the untrusted tier but can't reach your YNAB token.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Human approval gates
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 For any financial action above $X (you pick \'97 maybe $200), the agent proposes and you approve via iMessage rather than auto-executing. YES replies trigger the API call, anything else aborts.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Anomaly detection on the agent itself
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Log every API call the agent makes. A second simple script reviews these daily \'97 if the agent suddenly makes 50 YNAB POST calls in an hour when it normally makes 5, alert you. This catches compromise after the fact, which is a real safety net.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 My honest bottom-line assessment\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 OpenClaw is a legitimately powerful tool, and for lower-stakes use cases \'97 media control, home automation, casual chat \'97 the security risks are manageable. For high-stakes financial data, you're running an experimental, rapidly-evolving, well-targeted piece of software. That's doable but demands discipline.\cb1 \
\cb3 The practical question is:\'a0
\f2\b do the convenience gains justify the operational security burden?
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 For some of your planned use cases (iMessage interface, proactive morning digests, casual queries), OpenClaw adds real value. For the actual financial processing (YNAB reconciliation, Amazon categorization), you might honestly get 80% of the value with 20% of the risk by using plain Python scripts running via cron that don't need to be network-accessible or messaging-connected at all. The reconciliation script doesn't need to listen for incoming messages \'97 it just needs to run nightly, do its work, and email you a summary.\cb1 \
\cb3 A reasonable split:\'a0
\f2\b Python + YNAB API + Ollama
\f1\b0 \'a0handles the sensitive financial automation as a classic scheduled job, entirely internal, no messaging exposure.\'a0
\f2\b OpenClaw
\f1\b0 \'a0handles the lower-sensitivity user-facing layer \'97 morning digests, query responses, calendar integration \'97 with only read-only access to the finance data.\cb1 \
\cb3 That significantly reduces your attack surface while keeping most of the convenience. Given your engineering instincts, I suspect that hybrid approach will feel more comfortable than giving a single agent platform both the broad system access\'a0
\f5\i and
\f1\i0 \'a0the keys to your financial data.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

