\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 One last honest thought\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 The threat model for a technical, engaged retiree running this at home is fundamentally different from an enterprise deployment. You're not a high-value individual target, you're not exposing services to the internet, and you'll actually pay attention to audit logs and patches. That profile is much safer than the average OpenClaw user \'97 most attacks we've seen succeed because someone ran the agent with default settings on a cloud VPS without thinking about hardening at all.\cb1 \
\cb3 Your bigger risk is probably not a targeted attack but a mass campaign that sprays malicious emails or malicious skills hoping some percentage of installations fall for them. The hybrid architecture you're leaning toward, combined with basic hygiene, takes you out of the vulnerable population for most of those campaigns.\cb1 \
\cb3 That said \'97 given the financial stakes involved in retirement \'97 it's worth treating this as an evolving problem, not a solved one. Revisit your security setup every 6-12 months, read new OpenClaw release notes carefully, and be willing to walk back any integration that starts feeling too convenient-to-be-safe.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

