\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) changes everything
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Five of the six major open models now use mixture-of-experts: Llama 4 Scout (109B/17B active), Mistral Small 4 (119B/6.5B active), gpt-oss-120b (117B/5.1B active), GLM-5 (744B/40B active), and Qwen 3.6 Plus.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://www.digitalapplied.com/blog/open-source-ai-landscape-april-2026-gemma-qwen-llama"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf6 \cb7 Digital Applied\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\fs24 \cf2 \strokec2 \
}}\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 What this means practically: a "109B parameter" model only activates 17B per token, so it runs at roughly 17B speed while having 109B knowledge. The memory cost is the full 109B (quantized), but inference is fast.\cb1 \
\cb3 Qwen3-Coder-Next (80B total, 3B active) scores 71.3% on SWE-Bench Verified \'97 beating DeepSeek-V3.2 (671B, 37B active) while using 12x less compute per token. At Q4_K_M (48.5 GB), it fits on a Mac with 64GB unified memory.\'a0{\field{\*\fldinst{HYPERLINK "https://awesomeagents.ai/leaderboards/home-gpu-llm-leaderboard/"}}{\fldrslt 
\f0\fs18 \cf6 \cb1 \strokec6 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
