\ls54\ilvl0
\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Used M2 Pro Mac mini 32GB
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 roughly $850-1000 used, handles your full stack at 14B model level\cb1 \
\ls54\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Used Mac Studio M1 Max 64GB
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 around $1500-1800, comfortably runs 70B models\cb1 \
\ls54\ilvl0
\f2\b \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	\uc0\u8226 	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 Refurbished M4 Mac mini 24GB
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 when available through Apple directly, $679\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 This is probably your best path if you want iMessage and can't wait. A Mac Studio especially is interesting \'97 quieter than you'd think, far more capable than a mini, and the used market is active.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 Option 3 \'97 Swap iMessage for Telegram or Signal\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 This is honestly the decision worth thinking hardest about. Here's the case:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Telegram
\f1\b0 \'a0is the most common OpenClaw channel in the community \'97 better supported, more skills available, and works identically across all your devices. Signal and WhatsApp are both solid alternatives. All three are private (Signal most so), end-to-end encrypted, and run on iPhone just like iMessage.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The practical difference for your use case is small. You'd text a Telegram bot instead of an iMessage contact. The bot name in your contacts list looks slightly different. Everything else \'97 the convenience, the "text my assistant from anywhere" experience, the notifications \'97 is essentially identical.\cb1 \
\cb3 If you're willing to accept that one tradeoff, you open up the entire mini PC market. Which is where things get interesting.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 Mini PCs that would handle your stack well\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Assuming you're open to Telegram/Signal, here are the strong options:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 AMD Ryzen AI Max+ 395 mini PCs (Strix Halo)
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 These are the mini PC sensation of 2025-2026. They ship with up to 128GB of unified memory via AMD's new architecture \'97 explicitly designed for local AI workloads. Examples: GMKtec EVO-X2, Beelink GTR9 Pro, Framework Desktop. Prices start around $1,500 for 64GB configurations and $2,000-2,500 for 128GB. They run Linux or Windows, work perfectly with Ollama, and have become popular in the OpenClaw community.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Framework Desktop (Ryzen AI Max+ 395)
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Same chip, more upgradable, modular design, Framework's repair-friendly philosophy. Around $2,000 for 64GB. Genuinely exciting hardware that matches or exceeds Mac Studio performance for LLM workloads.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 GMKtec / Minisforum AMD mini PCs
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 The value tier. AMD Ryzen 9 with 64GB RAM, no dedicated NPU but still runs models via CPU inference or integrated graphics. Around $800-1,200. Slower than Apple Silicon or the AI Max+ chips, but workable for your finance automation use case.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Intel NUC-class with discrete GPU
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 Beelink or Minisforum units with RTX 4060/4070 included. About $1,200-1,800. Higher power draw, more fan noise, but genuine GPU inference speed.\cb1 \
\
