\f1 \cf2 \cb3 Honestly? For your specific situation, I lean toward\'a0
\f2\b mostly building your own, with OpenClaw as a small optional layer later \'97 or skipping it entirely.
\f1\b0 \cb1 \
\cb3 Here's the genuine reasoning, not the enthusiastic version:\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 What OpenClaw actually gives you\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Strip away the marketing and what you're really paying for is:\cb1 \
\pard\tx220\tx720\pardeftab720\li720\fi-720\partightenfactor0
\ls57\ilvl0\cf2 \cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	1	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A messaging abstraction layer (connects chat apps to your scripts)\cb1 \
\ls57\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	2	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A persistent memory system (context across conversations)\cb1 \
\ls57\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	3	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A scheduler (cron wrapped in natural language)\cb1 \
\ls57\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	4	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 A skill plugin architecture (community extensibility)\cb1 \
\ls57\ilvl0\cb3 \kerning1\expnd0\expndtw0 \outl0\strokewidth0 {\listtext	5	}\expnd0\expndtw0\kerning0
\outl0\strokewidth0 \strokec2 An agent runtime (conversation management, tool calling)\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0
\cf2 \cb3 That's genuinely useful... for someone who needs those abstractions. But let's look at each one for your case specifically.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 Evaluating each piece for you\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Messaging abstraction
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 You want iMessage to your own system. A plain Python script using\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf12 \cb13 \strokec12 imessage-exporter
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0or AppleScript bindings hits iMessage directly with maybe 50 lines of code. OpenClaw adds hundreds of MB of infrastructure to do the same thing. Winner: your own code.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Persistent memory
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 SQLite tables you design specifically for your data (transactions, categorization corrections, spending patterns) will outperform OpenClaw's generic memory system for your use case. You know exactly what you need to remember. Winner: your own code.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Scheduler
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 macOS has\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf12 \cb13 \strokec12 launchd
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 \'a0and\'a0
\f0\fs21\fsmilli10800 \cf12 \cb13 \strokec12 cron
\f1\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 \strokec2 . They run reliably, have worked for decades, and don't need a 500MB agent runtime to invoke a Python script at 7am. Winner: built-in macOS.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Skill plugin architecture
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 This is only valuable if you're consuming others' skills. For personal finance automation, no community skill will know your specific YNAB categories, your household's spending patterns, or your preferences. You'd end up writing custom skills anyway. Winner: your own code.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Agent runtime
\f1\b0 \'a0\'97 The one genuine value-add. Multi-turn conversations with tool calling is hard to replicate cleanly. But... Ollama + a few hundred lines of Python using the OpenAI-compatible API handles this for simple cases. Winner: depends on complexity.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 The hidden costs of OpenClaw\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 These are the ones that matter:\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b \cf2 \cb3 Security surface area.
\f1\b0 \'a0Every OpenClaw install is an attack target. Every patch cycle is homework. Every community skill you consider is a vetting exercise. For a retirement setup where you want "installed once, works for years," that ongoing burden is real.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Opacity.
\f1\b0 \'a0When something goes wrong, debugging OpenClaw's skill orchestration is harder than debugging your own Python. You end up reading Node.js internals to figure out why a skill didn't fire.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 Velocity churn.
\f1\b0 \'a0OpenClaw is iterating fast. Skills break with updates. Documentation lags. Community skills get deprecated. You'll spend time keeping up with a platform, not building your actual project.\cb1 \

\f2\b \cb3 The "agent" abstraction can be wrong.
\f1\b0 \'a0OpenClaw assumes conversational turns with tool calls. Your actual finance automation is mostly\'a0
\f5\i scheduled jobs that email/text you results
\f1\i0 . Forcing that into an agent framework adds complexity without benefit.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

