\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 My honest recommendation\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Build it yourself. Here's the concrete case:\cb1 \
\cb3 Your actual use case \'97 nightly transaction categorization, Amazon reconciliation, morning digests, weekly summaries, monthly retirement checks \'97 is\'a0
\f2\b overwhelmingly scheduled deterministic automation, not conversational agent work
\f1\b0 . That's not what OpenClaw is optimized for. It's what cron and Python have been optimized for since 1975.\cb1 \
\cb3 The one place OpenClaw would shine is if you want to ask ad-hoc questions via iMessage: "Hey, how much did we spend on groceries last month?" But even this is solvable with a simple Python script listening for iMessage pings and routing to Ollama. A weekend project, not a platform adoption.\cb1 \
\cb3 Start with your own code. If six months in you find yourself wishing you had a conversational agent layer for ad-hoc queries, install OpenClaw\'a0
\f5\i then
\f1\i0 , limited to that one job, with your existing Python scripts continuing to do the heavy lifting. You get the best of both worlds and you've already validated that you actually need the agent layer.\cb1 \
\
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 The broader principle for your retirement projects\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 You're a mechanical engineer who managed manufacturing teams. You think in systems, you value understanding what you've built, and you have time to do things properly rather than racing to deploy. That disposition is honestly a better fit for "build what you need from first principles" than "adopt a trendy platform and fight with its abstractions."\cb1 \
\cb3 OpenClaw is genuinely impressive software and the community is doing cool things. But it's a platform optimized for people who want to move fast and accept complexity in exchange for speed. You can move at your own pace, build exactly what fits your life, and have a system that's fully yours \'97 legible, debuggable, and not subject to upstream churn.\cb1 \
\cb3 For a retirement build that should quietly work for years, your own code is the more durable choice.\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

