\f2\b\fs27 \cf2 \cb3 My honest recommendation updated\cb1 \
\pard\pardeftab720\partightenfactor0

\f1\b0\fs24 \cf2 \cb3 Your core plan doesn't change. Build the finance automation in Python, let scheduled jobs handle the heavy lifting, keep your attack surface minimal. That's still right.\cb1 \
\cb3 But if six months in, you find yourself wishing for that conversational ad-hoc query layer \'97 "what did we spend on groceries last month?", "remind me to check the roth conversion deadline" \'97\'a0
\f2\b Hermes Agent is probably a better fit than OpenClaw for your specific situation
\f1\b0 . The security posture is better, the architecture is more aligned with scheduled automation rather than constant conversation, and the BlueBubbles iMessage integration is officially supported.\cb1 \
\cb3 Given you've already got the Mac mini arriving soon, I'd follow the original plan through: Ollama first, then Python finance scripts, then validate it all works for a few months. Only after that do you even evaluate whether you want an agent framework on top. If you do, look at Hermes first rather than OpenClaw.\cb1 \
\cb3 The question isn't "OpenClaw or Hermes?" \'97 it's "should I add an agent layer at all, and if I eventually do, which one?" For now, the answer remains: build your own foundation, see what you actually need.\cb1 \
